Anti-Patterns to Avoid
These patterns make blueprints unreliable. Never produce them.

1. Vague best-practice references
Wrong: "Use best practices for error handling."

Why it fails: Different coding agents interpret best practices differently. The result is inconsistent implementations across sessions and agents.

Correct: Specify the exact mechanism: "Wrap all repository calls in Result. Map IOException to AppError.NoInternet. Surface all errors to UiState.Error with a user-readable message and an optional retryAction lambda."

2. Deferred error handling
Wrong: "Add error handling as needed during implementation."

Why it fails: Error handling is never added later. The coding agent skips it, and error states are missing entirely from the final app.

Correct: Define error handling strategy explicitly in Phase 5 and enforce it in the AI Implementation Contract in Phase 17.

3. Undefined architecture shorthand
Wrong: "Standard MVVM setup."

Why it fails: MVVM means different things to different agents — some skip the domain layer, some expose MutableStateFlow publicly, some call Retrofit from the ViewModel.

Correct: Fully define each layer's responsibilities, what it is allowed to call, and what it is forbidden from doing. Phase 5 exists for this reason.

4. TBD placeholders in the blueprint
Wrong: "Navigation to be designed later." "Database schema TBD."

Why it fails: The coding agent blocks on design decisions, invents its own approach, or produces inconsistent results across sessions.

Correct: Every phase must be complete before the blueprint is delivered. Never use TBD.

5. Screens without UI states
Wrong: Listing a screen name without defining its Loading, Success, Empty, and Error states.

Why it fails: The coding agent guesses which states exist and produces inconsistent UX. Some screens get a loading spinner, others show blank content.

Correct: Every screen in Phase 3 must define all four base UI states with a description of what each one shows the user.

6. Libraries without versions
Wrong: "Use Retrofit for networking."

Why it fails: The coding agent picks whatever version it knows about, which may be outdated, incompatible with other dependencies, or introduce breaking API changes.

Correct: Specify the exact artifact ID and latest stable version for every library in Phase 12.

7. Open-ended folder structure
Wrong: "Add packages as needed during development."

Why it fails: Different agents create inconsistent package layouts. Features end up in random locations with no discoverable structure.

Correct: Define the complete folder structure in Phase 13 before implementation begins. Every directory must have a documented purpose.

8. Missing AI Implementation Contract
Wrong: Delivering a blueprint with no Phase 17.

Why it fails: The coding agent falls back to personal defaults: mixed Kotlin/Java, wrong dispatcher choices, LiveData instead of StateFlow, hardcoded strings, and more.

Correct: Phase 17 is mandatory. It is the final authority the coding agent consults before writing any line of code. Every standard must be explicit and unambiguous.

9. Starting to plan without clarifying the idea
Wrong: Receiving a vague idea and jumping directly to Phase 1.

Why it fails: The blueprint describes the wrong app. Work must be discarded and restarted after the user clarifies requirements — after significant effort has already been spent.

Correct: Always evaluate the idea against the golden-rule questions in Phase 0. Ask counter-questions before any planning work begins.
